    "narrative_summary": "The TP53 c.666G>A (p.Pro222=) variant is a synonymous change in the tumor\u2011suppressor gene TP53 that has been reported in cancer\u2011gene screening studies and is listed in ClinVar under the identifier NM_000546.5:c.666G>A.  Although TP53 mutations are classically associated with Li\u2011Fraumeni syndrome and a broad spectrum of malignancies, this particular nucleotide substitution does not alter the encoded amino\u2011acid sequence.\nClinical data from several cohorts consistently describe the variant as non\u2011pathogenic.  In an Iranian lung\u2011cancer series the authors classified c.666G>A as a novel benign variant and argued that it is likely non\u2011pathogenic despite being detected in the patient cohort [PMC6061986].  A ClinVar supplemental table records the same change as \u201cLikely benign\u201d with multiple submitters and no conflicts [PMC6672031].  A large Japanese case\u2011control study of breast\u2011cancer susceptibility genes also listed the variant as a benign synonymous alteration [PMC6172276].  An article on Lynch\u2011syndrome diagnostics mentions the variant but provides no pathogenicity claim, further indicating the absence of disease association [PMC5303590].\nFunctional investigations are lacking.  One recent analysis of termination\u2011codon evolution erroneously listed c.666G>A as a nonsense mutation generating a stop codon (p.W222*), but no experimental data supporting a deleterious effect were presented, and the annotation appears inconsistent with the synonymous nature of the change [PMC10471768].  No in\u2011vitro or in\u2011vivo functional assays have been reported for this variant.\nPopulation\u2011level data show the allele to be rare, with a minor\u2011allele frequency of approximately 6.7\u202f\u00d7\u202f10\u207b\u2075 in the Iranian cohort [PMC6061986].  The Japanese cohort also identified the variant among thousands of screened individuals but did not report an elevated frequency in cases versus controls, reinforcing its classification as benign.  No computational prediction scores are provided in the extracted evidence.\nOverall, the preponderance of evidence from clinical databases and population screening studies supports a benign interpretation of TP53 c.666G>A.  The lack of functional impact data and the rarity of the allele, combined with consistent \u201clikely benign\u201d or \u201cbenign\u201d designations in multiple independent reports, lead to the conclusion that this synonymous TP53 variant does not confer increased disease risk.",
